[1] Georgia: feline, canine, raccoon, human exposure
Date: Fri 3 Mar 2017
Source: The Daily Citizen [edited]
http://www.daltondailycitizen.com/news/local_news/cat-that-bit-woman-tests-positive-for-rabies/article_b45d2f0b-010a-5f52-a4e6-5d07bf5d1b50.html


A domesticated cat that bit a woman in the Dawnville area Tuesday night [28 Feb 2017] has testified positive for rabies, the Whitfield County [Georgia] rabies control officer said [Fri 3 Mar 2017].

David Hedden said the incident happened on Mark Brown Road off of Mitchell Bridge Road. The woman is having to take rabies shots, he said. [This is the post exposure prophylaxis (PEP) series to prevent the rabies virus from killing her. - Mod.TG]

Hedden said officials are encouraging everyone to make sure their pets are vaccinated against rabies, which is required under state law.

He said it is important that people do not approach any animal that is acting in a strange manner. If you see such an animal, call 911, he said.

The North Georgia Health District said on 24 Feb 2017 a Whitfield County dog was recently bitten by a raccoon that had since tested positive for rabies. The dog was unvaccinated and is undergoing a 6-month quarantine. That incident happened at a residence on Dogwood Drive off Pine Hill Road and East Morris Street in Dalton. The dog fought back and killed the raccoon.

Hedden said this is the 5th case of rabies detected in the county in the last 8 or 9 months.

Hedden and officials with Whitfield County Environmental Health and Whitfield County Animal Control have been passing out fliers in these areas to warn residents of the presence of rabies.

The North Georgia Health District said in the press release on 24 Feb 2017, "Residents should be wary of unfamiliar animals, and parents should take special care to inform their children about rabies, telling children to avoid stray dogs and cats, as well as wild animals, and to report any such contacts or bites at once."

Ray King, director of Environmental Health for the North Georgia Health District, said, "The chance of dying from rabies is almost 100 percent if the exposed person is not given preventive treatments soon after exposure. Rabies is a horrible way to die."

Raccoons are the most common animal found with rabies in Georgia, the health district said, but many other species can contract rabies such as skunks, foxes, bobcats, coyotes, and bats. Livestock can also contract rabies from wild animals and it is "strongly recommended" that livestock that have regular contact with humans be vaccinated.

Suspicious animals that appear aggressive or sick can also be reported to Whitfield County Animal Control.

